  "solution": "The high-performing ED has likely decoupled perceived responsiveness from physical capacity. Research on HCAHPS/Press Ganey scores consistently shows that patient satisfaction in EDs is driven more by communication quality, expectation-setting, and acknowledgment than by actual wait times.\n\nSpecifically, they are probably doing:\n1. **Immediate acknowledgment / rapid intake** — patients are seen by a provider within minutes of arrival, even briefly, eliminating the 'invisible in the waiting room' experience\n2. **Proactive communication protocols** — staff tell patients what's happening and when, unprompted; uncertainty is the primary driver of dissatisfaction, not duration\n3. **Split-flow / lean throughput models** — lower-acuity patients treated in chairs/fast-track lanes without ever occupying a bed, cycling faster and never boarding\n4. **Protocols that don't degrade under surge** — their satisfaction processes are staff-behavior-based, not space-based, so volume doesn't break them the same way\n\nThe real driver: satisfaction is a psychological experience, not an operational metric. Patients can tolerate long waits if they feel attended to, informed, and respected. They become dissatisfied quickly when they feel invisible.\n\nWhat winter volume actually breaks is *staff bandwidth for human interaction*, not bed count. Adding more beds under the same interaction model just enables ignoring more patients simultaneously.\n\nImplication: The ED should audit *communication breakdown under surge* — do nurses round less frequently? Do patients wait longer for acknowledgment? — before assuming the fix is more physical capacity. The high-scoring anomaly suggests the leverage point is operational behavior, not infrastructure."
